    "requestId": "9e1371d377efc0dd82b622d608273dfa",
    "answer": "The market opportunity for autonomous AI agents that self-fund via token swap fees on Base appears to be highly promising and rapidly evolving. Recent developments highlight that tokenized agents on Base are generating substantial revenue, with reports of a tokenized agent earning around $10,000 daily ([blockchain.news](https://blockchain.news/flashnews/tokenized-agent-on-base-generates-10k-daily-revenue)). This indicates a strong potential for these agents to create sustainable income streams through fee-based mechanisms like token swaps, which are integral to their operation and funding.\n\nFurthermore, Base’s ecosystem supports building and deploying such autonomous agents, with documentation outlining capabilities for agents to hold funds, execute token swaps, and interact with various DeFi protocols ([Base docs](https://docs.base.org/ai-agents)). The emergence of self-funding, autonomous agent fleets—such as those managed by AGIFund—demonstrates that these agents can autonomously trade, stake, and refill their wallets from profits, effectively creating a self-sustaining economic loop ([AInvest](https://www.ainvest.com/news/agentscan-launch-flow-based-analysis-ai-agent-discovery-base-2602), [AGIFund](http://agi-fund.xyz)). \n\nMarket analyses suggest that the convergence of decentralized finance, large language models, and blockchain infrastructure is fostering a new \"Agentic Economy,\" where AI agents act as independent economic actors, launching tokens, managing treasuries, and generating revenue through fee mechanisms like token swaps ([IZHC](https://zhcinstitute.com/research/agentic-singularity), [Cambrian](https://www.cambrian.org/blog/agentic-finance-landscape-q1-2026)). The combination of high network activity, institutional partnerships, and innovative protocols positions this sector for significant growth, making it a compelling opportunity for investors and developers interested in autonomous, self-funding AI agents on Base.",
