    "answer": "When comparing Bankr, OpenRouter, and direct API calls for LLM inference, several factors such as cost per token, latency, and use cases are important.\n\n**Cost per token** varies depending on the provider and the gateway setup. Bankr offers a unified billing system that can fund usage via launch fees or wallet balances, potentially optimizing costs through flexible payment options and multi-provider access ([Bankr Documentation](https://docs.bankr.bot/llm-gateway/overview)). OpenRouter, as a multi-model gateway, routes requests to multiple providers and models, with latency overhead around 50-70ms and some provider-specific feature limitations, but it can reduce costs by dynamically selecting the cheapest or fastest provider ([Skywork.ai](https://skywork.ai/blog/openrouter-review-2025-api-gateway-latency-pricing)). Direct API calls typically involve paying per token directly to each provider, which can be more expensive but offers maximum control over costs and features ([BSWEN](https://docs.bswen.com/blog/2026-03-06-openrouter-vs-api-vs-subscriptions)).\n\n**Latency benchmarks** show that direct API calls generally have lower latency since they avoid routing overhead, but OpenRouter introduces an additional 50-70ms latency overhead due to its routing layer. Bankr's unified API aims for high availability with automatic failover, and latency depends on the underlying provider and network conditions ([Skywork.ai](https://skywork.ai/blog/openrouter-review-2025-api-gateway-latency-pricing), [Bankr Documentation](https://docs.bankr.bot/llm-gateway/api-reference)). For autonomous agents requiring quick responses, direct API calls are typically preferable if latency is critical.\n\n**Best use cases**:  \n- **Bankr** is ideal for applications needing flexible payments, cost tracking, and multi-provider access with high availability ([Bankr Documentation](https://docs.bankr.bot/llm-gateway/overview)).  \n- **OpenRouter** suits scenarios where multi-model routing, cost optimization, and simplified API management are priorities, especially when integrating multiple providers or models ([Skywork.ai](https://skywork.ai/blog/openrouter-review-2025-api-gateway-latency-pricing)).  \n- **Direct API calls** are best for use cases demanding minimal latency, maximum control, and potentially lower costs when only a single provider is used.\n\nIn summary, the choice depends on whether the priority is cost efficiency, latency, or ease of multi-provider management. OpenRouter and Bankr provide abstraction layers that simplify multi-model access at some latency and cost trade-offs, while direct API calls offer the lowest latency and highest control but may incur higher costs and management complexity ([Skywork.ai](https://skywork.ai/blog/openrouter-review-2025-api-gateway-latency-pricing), [BSWEN](https://docs.bswen.com/blog/2026-03-06-openrouter-vs-api-vs-subscriptions)).",
