    "answer": "ERC-8004, ENS, and Lens Protocol are distinct approaches for AI agent identity and trust, each with different features, costs, and suitability for agent-to-agent trust. \n\nERC-8004 is an Ethereum standard that creates trustless, on-chain identities for AI agents through registries for identity, reputation, and validation. It enables discoverability, reputation signals, and validation mechanisms, making it suitable for establishing trust in decentralized, permissionless environments, especially for high-stakes interactions ([Result 5](https://rnwy.com/learn/erc-8004-trustless-agents), [Result 8](https://www.datawallet.com/crypto/erc-8004-explained)). Its design emphasizes cryptographic verification, reputation, and stake-based validation, which are critical for secure agent-to-agent trust.\n\nENS (Ethereum Name Service), on the other hand, primarily provides a naming and discovery layer for on-chain identities, enabling human-readable names for blockchain addresses and assets. While ENS facilitates agent discovery and identification, it does not inherently include reputation or trust validation features ([Result 4](https://ens.domains/blog/post/ens-ai-agent-erc8004)). Its focus is more on naming and discovery rather than comprehensive trust mechanisms.\n\nLens Protocol is a social graph protocol designed for social identities and reputation on Web3, emphasizing social connections and reputation signals. It is more suited for identity verification based on social trust and community signals rather than the cryptographic or stake-based validation mechanisms central to ERC-8004 ([No specific result, but based on known functionality]).\n\nIn terms of cost, ERC-8004 involves on-chain registration, reputation, and validation transactions, which can incur gas fees, especially for high-stakes validation mechanisms like zk-proofs or stake slashing. ENS registration is generally cheaper, focusing on name registration and resolution, while Lens Protocol's costs depend on social activity and data storage but are typically lower than complex cryptographic validation.\n\nFor agent-to-agent trust, ERC-8004 offers the most comprehensive framework with cryptographic proofs, reputation, and stake-based validation, making it suitable for secure, trustless interactions. ENS provides basic discovery and identity, useful for initial identification but lacking trust validation. Lens Protocol adds social trust signals, which may be useful for community-based trust but less for cryptographically secure interactions.\n\n**Summary:**  \n- **ERC-8004**: Best for trustless, cryptographically secured agent identities with validation, suitable for high-stakes agent interactions.  \n- **ENS**: Good for discovery and naming, less for validation or trust.  \n- **Lens Protocol**: Focuses on social reputation and community trust, more for social identity than cryptographic trust.  \n\nChoosing the right depends on your trust model needs, with ERC-8004 being the most feature-rich for agent-to-agent trust ([Results 1, 5, 8](https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-8004), [Result 4](https://ens.domains/blog/post/ens-ai-agent-erc8004)).",
