    "answer": "To increase your chances of winning crypto hackathons in 2026, focus on proven strategies highlighted in recent guides and expert advice. \n\nFirst, **understand what judges look for**: they evaluate based on clear, specific criteria such as code quality, creativity, innovation, and how well your project aligns with the hackathon’s goals ([DoraHacks](https://dorahacks.io/blog/guides/hackathon-judging-plan), [Medium](https://medium.com/hidorahacks/how-to-design-a-hackathon-judging-a5b0d8d4d9d4)). Be sure to **read the requirements thoroughly** and submit complete, well-presented projects that are easy to evaluate ([DoraHacks](https://dorahacks.io/blog/news/good-hackathon-submission), [Medium](https://hidorahacks.medium.com/what-does-a-good-hackathon-submission-look-like-1500c24592a2)).\n\nSecond, **prepare your project in advance**: have your tech stack, scaffolds, and demo scripts ready before the event starts. Build a **small, impactful demo** that showcases a key feature end-to-end, rather than overloading with features ([DoraNoda](https://blockeden.xyz/blog/2025/07/07/web3-hackathons-done-right)). \n\nThird, **choose the right event and track**: pick hackathons aligned with your expertise and goals, whether for learning, bounties, or competition ([DoraNoda](https://blockeden.xyz/blog/2025/07/07/web3-hackathons-done-right)). \n\nFinally, **submit professionally**: follow submission guidelines carefully, create a compelling presentation or demo video, and clearly communicate your project’s value ([DoraHacks](https://dorahacks.io/blog/guides/hackathon-judging-plan), [Medium](https://hidorahacks.medium.com/what-does-a-good-hackathon-submission-look-like-1500c24592a2)). \n\nStaying organized, focused on impactful features, and understanding judging criteria are key to standing out and winning in 2026 crypto hackathons.",
