    "answer": "For agent payments using USDC, Base, Arbitrum, and Optimism each offer distinct advantages in gas costs, bridge times, liquidity, and suitability for AI agent treasuries.\n\n**Gas costs:** All three Layer 2 solutions significantly reduce transaction fees compared to Ethereum mainnet. USDC on Base typically costs under $0.01 per transaction with confirmation times around 2 seconds, making it highly cost-effective for frequent payments ([USDC.org](https://usdc.org/usdc/base)). Arbitrum and Optimism also offer low fees, with Arbitrum's multi-round fraud proofs often resulting in slightly lower fees than Optimism's single-round approach, which can be marginally more expensive due to its faster, L1-influenced execution ([payram.com](https://payram.com/blog/arbitrum-vs-optimism-vs-base), [coinmarketcap.com](https://coinmarketcap.com/academy/article/arbitrum-vs-optimism-the-ultimate-comparison)).\n\n**Bridge times:** Bridge times vary, but generally, Base provides near-instant transfers (~2 seconds) for USDC, facilitating quick onboarding and transactions ([USDC.org](https://usdc.org/usdc/base)). Arbitrum and Optimism also support rapid bridging, often completing transfers within a few minutes, though exact times depend on network congestion ([arbitrum.io](https://docs.arbitrum.io/how-arbitrum-works/deep-dives/gas-and-fees)).\n\n**Liquidity and DEX support:** Base has a rapidly growing ecosystem with deep liquidity on DEXs like Aerodrome, making it suitable for trading and liquidity management ([USDC.org](https://usdc.org/usdc/base)). Arbitrum and Optimism also host major DeFi protocols, with Arbitrum’s multi-round fraud proofs providing efficient gas usage, and Optimism leveraging its faster single-round fraud proofs for quicker transactions ([coincreate.io](https://resources.coincreate.io/arbitrum-vs-base-vs-optimism-which-ethereum-l2-should-you-use-2026)).\n\n**Best for AI agent treasuries:** For AI agents managing treasuries, Base’s low fees, quick confirmation times, and expanding ecosystem make it an attractive option for cost-efficient, high-frequency transactions. Its integration with Coinbase and broad application support further enhance its suitability. Arbitrum and Optimism are also strong contenders, especially if multi-chain liquidity or specific protocol features are prioritized.\n\nIn summary, **Base** currently offers the lowest costs and fastest confirmations for USDC transactions, making it ideal for agent payments and treasury management, with Arbitrum and Optimism providing competitive alternatives depending on specific protocol needs and liquidity considerations ([0xprocessing.com](https://0xprocessing.com/blog/layer-2-battles-base-vs-arbitrum-vs-optimism-which-is-best-for-merchant-payments)).",
