    "answer": "Multi-agent collaboration patterns involve how AI agents can discover, establish trust, and transact with each other within complex systems. Protocols like x402, ERC-8004, and A2A are central to enabling these interactions by providing standardized frameworks for payments, identity, and communication. For instance, x402 is a payment protocol that extends HTTP, allowing agents to perform transactions seamlessly on the web by attaching signed transactions to HTTP requests, which has processed over 35 million transactions and $10 million in volume on Solana ([moltx.io](https://moltx.io/articles/416a6010-f6b7-4ff8-80f1-68cbd5882e0f)). ERC-8004, on the other hand, focuses on establishing trustless agents through blockchain-based identity, reputation, and validation registries, enabling agents to discover and interact without pre-existing trust, suitable for open-ended agent economies ([ethereum.org](https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-8004)). \n\nA2A (Agent-to-Agent) protocols facilitate direct communication and coordination between agents, often leveraging standards like EIP-712 for secure message signing and verification, which is crucial for trust and responsibility delegation in multi-agent systems ([chaincatcher.com](https://www.chaincatcher.com/en/article/2220513)). These protocols collectively support the development of decentralized, autonomous AI ecosystems where agents can find, verify, and transact with each other reliably and securely, fostering more scalable and trustworthy multi-agent collaborations ([knowyouragent.network](https://knowyouragent.network/erc-8004-x402-the-complete-stack-for-ai-agent-commerce)).",
